The theme for this year's project is Data for Social Good. 
Our project makes it more easier for users to get information and resources they need in terms of job search and accommodation. 
Our draft interim report is detailed in this blog post.


#  Interim Report

#                  Team Name: JobMap





## User Scenario: The Characters

Who is your target user?

The theme for this year&#39;s project is Data for Social Good. Our makes it more easier for users to get information and resources they need in terms of job search and accommodation. Our target user is basically everyone who is looking for a job and planning on starting a new career or exploring a new career option in various geographic regions in Ireland or even the place they currently are residing in. Since most of us faced have faced similar situations, our own experience has helped us in developing the concept of a website that displays the visualized information of aggregated jobs, housing on the same screen. We believe that this project can help with &quot;social good&quot; by making relocation easier to locations around Ireland..

Why are they important?

To build a better system we need to identify the problems that are being faced by the general crowd, and try coming up with a solution that resolves or diminishes the problems. The only way the problems are identified is by experiencing them or by communicating with different people and identifying the problems that are faced in general. Once a certain problem is identified the next approach in dissolving that problem would be by designing or developing a product/system that reduces it. Once the system is designed the next approach would be in trying to see how well the designed system performs and how well would that be adopted by the users. In achieving all of these approaches the main key role played would be by the User, so they play a very crucial role from problem identification to solving that by verifying, testing and suggesting many different ideas and thoughts.At the end of the day, whatever system is designed needs to serve some particular purpose and that purpose for us in our system is how the User responds to our system and uses them.

What problem are you solving for them?

 There are people who want to move to a different place to start a new career just to have a new experience, but most of the time end up on compromising either on the job or on the accomodation. Also people who want to move to the city in search of jobs find it hard to find accommodation close to where they work. Having faced such issues and still facing we knew how important or how essential this project could be to the end user. As much as the project would be important, our end users are also equally important to us because without them there would be no purpose for the project. The solution that we designed for this issue is by aggregating jobs and accommodation information and displaying them in a visualized maps and graphs. The webpage would be an integrated screen where the user can view how the job trend has evolved over the past years based on the user search of job industry and location, along with the current job information. By this the user would be able to figure out the job they need with comfortable accommodations available near by and also look out and analyse the job trend. This approach could perhaps save users with time and help them become more organised in their planning for the future life.

## **Technical Problem: The Setting**

Why does your system exist?

The objective of the solution is to help address the social problem of over-urbanization by making it easier for people to find jobs and resources for moving to the right place for them. We are doing this by aggregating data from multiple sources and presenting the data visually to make it clearer than textual representation.

A major impediment to the movement of people is the availability of jobs. As an example, a 2017 report by Indecon found that employment was the 3rd biggest barrier to returning emigrants after housing and motor related issues (Table 4.1 [https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa-2017/globalirish/Report-on-Returning-Emigrants-2018.pdf](https://www.dfa.ie/media/dfa-2017/globalirish/Report-on-Returning-Emigrants-2018.pdf))

We expect the system to be useful to various types of migrants:

- People looking to relocate to Ireland from other countries. These could be returning emigrants or other immigrants.
- People already in Ireland looking to relocate to a different part of the country

What is the core technical problem?

At a high level, the technical problem is to provide a centralised aggregation of the resources a user needs for relocation. The core technical problem we have focused on is the visual presentation of jobs information. We are then complementing this with information on accommodation.

Currently, a user would have to access multiple websites or applications separately. They then have to correlate the information derived from the different sites to gain a more complete picture.

As an example scenario,

1. A user would check a jobs site (or multiple jobs sites) for job listings
2. For each listing that is of interest, the user would search for the office location on a map
3. The user would then goes to a housing website to look up housing information
4. They may then also look up  information about schools in the area

What our solution does is present this information aggregated information on a map to aid visualisation.

Can you review other existing systems or products that address this problem?

From our research, there are existing solutions that address various aspects of our solutions in isolation. There is no solution that provides the breadth of our solution. Broadly, the existing solutions fall into the following categories:

- Visual point in time snapshots of jobs data. These provide a visualisation similar to what we are using but are based purely on historical data. An example is the visualisation on [http://www.robertmanduca.com/projects/jobs.html](http://www.robertmanduca.com/projects/jobs.html)

- Jobs sites showing job listings at a county level but without the drilldown to a more detailed map representation. An example from jobs.ie is shown in the image below. Clicking on a county simply provides job listings for the county.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

- Another category is  interactive maps (generally based on Google maps API) to show information about properties. This captures one aspect of what our application will provide, however, our focus is different as our primary concentration is on jobs.

The key distinctions of our proposition is that we are

- Aggregating data from multiple sources that are of interest when relocating: Jobs, housing
- Enabling users to drilldown to the location of a listed job using the interactive Google maps API. The power of this approach is that the user gets the flexibility to examine the location in some depth.

## **Technical Solution: The Plot**

What does your system do?

From the user stories we realized that a typical user needs to search through various websites and access various resources manually and physically to get the information about the jobs, accommodation near their job location and various other information about the regular resources like schools. We outlined these requirements and decided on designing a website that would visualize such basic information in terms of maps.

Our system acts as a single interface for the information on jobs and accommodations along with visualizing the historical trend of jobs in that particular region. It showcases an aggregated information of the data collected from various resources and then visualizing them altogether in terms of graphs and maps.

Based on user search, system displays the trend of that particular job evolution along the past years with displaying the jobs that are currently present in the country. User can narrow down their search by zooming into the map for a specific region and look for the possible jobs within that region. The system navigates to the job hosting page when user clicks onto a particular job.

How does it work? (System diagram)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**       **

Front-end: Technologies, User interface components including interface mock-ups

Our front-end is mix of Google map API and MapBox API along with JavaScript to show the trends across industries as a heatmap.
MapBox = [https://www.mapbox.com/developers/](https://www.mapbox.com/developers/)
Google map API : [https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/tutorial](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/tutorial)

Back-end: Technical components

The backend utilises python running on the Django framework, as well a local MySQL database instance. We will retrieve data from the APIs for local storage on a MySQL database. The data retrieval will be scheduled using Celery. The diagram of our backend components is provided below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Data: What data resources are you going to use and how will you access, collect, and store them?

The are many rich websites that contain the information of jobs and accommodation but not all of them provide access to the data. We have confirmed access to the following sites that provide APIs for data collection or authorise scraping - jobs.ie, Glassdoor, Indeed and UCD Careers Connect. For accommodation data, we have confirmed access to UCD accommodation pad and Roomster. We are also retrieving data from the CSO to show historical trends for industries.

Most of the websites provide a service like RESTFUL Interface and XML to easily scrape the data. So we are using python for data collection. For the remainder, the solution is to parse the website from browser for data collection.

The data from the websites is initially collected and parsed, then preprocessed, cleaned and stored in MySQL.

## **Evaluation: The Reviews**

What does success look like for your system?

Our system aims at providing people interested in moving to or out of major cities in Ireland looking for work, the system will be called a success if it is able to provide all the required information to the user regarding Jobs in a city, industry trends and housing condition near the job location. If the information provided by the system helps our user to get a clear picture for moving from city to another then we can call it a successful system.

The ultimate goal of our system is to be able to provide a stable platform where the users can navigate to the location of available jobs and possibly find a suitable home and other amenities around. The aim is to deliver these features at one stop shop instead of them having to look through a number of sites which provide more of a textual based information. The visualization which envelops the data helps the users to cut through the visual information overload and provides a cleaner view of what they are looking for. If the user is able to navigate through the website and filter options based on their career, zoom in on their preferred location to choose the right job for them without any hindrance, that we believe is a success.

How will you evaluate the system that you built?

During the process of building the system we are already trying to reach out to people who have either moved or at least planned to move out of a city in ireland, their feedback is already making our system better. Therefore it would make a lot of sense to test the system with these people as it was their requirement once and can provide valuable feedback.

- We will have users test the system and compare to how they would have worked without the system.

- Evaluation will be based on user experience survey
- Evaluation will also based on a time comparison

Comparative analysis with another existing system would not suit us as the ideas we are trying to implement within our system is unique to the problem being solved. Resources are drawn from several different services that provide for a similar thought and action but not an integrated solution. We can get our test users to try it both ways and record the results like time taken, experience and overall usability of the systems. This way we will have some concrete facts on how our system will perform as compared to the ones that already exists. UCD&#39;s Career office can evaluate our system and see it as a job portal for graduate students. Having students use the system will give us realistic expectations on designing the system for the people. This will further allow us to gain some feedback and improve the performance of the system.

## **Conclusion: The Plan**

What is your project management strategy?

Agile methods were adopted to have a smooth communication between the members of the team rather than traditional methods like the waterfall model which according to our understanding would invite errors and needs a great deal of certainty upfront which does not help when new changes are incorporated. A &quot;daily scrum&quot; meet or a &quot;stand-up&quot; was organized to brief the team on the tasks completed, tasks to be done and if there were any impediments. The progress and updates during the discussion was recorded using Trello, a web-based project management application which was part of the Kanban approach that allowed us to create tasks and monitor the progress by switching tasks across &quot;to-do&quot; and &quot;done&quot; swimlanes. The scrum/Kanban methods helped us receive feedback in fast and short increments and enabled us to stay updated on the progress and adapt to the changing requirements. The focus is to serve the audience/user and so framing features from the user&#39;s perspective was the ultimate goal. User stories, scenarios, personas were designed to understand the user better and their needs to solve the problem, interviews were conducted to keep a record of real life challenges faced by people who migrate to cities in search for jobs in their respective fields.

What are the biggest challenges you are currently facing?

The biggest challenges faced by the team currently is: identifying resources to gather data from; to request permission and gain access to the APIs that enable us to extract data; generating URLs for the websites depending on the data that was secured. On the front-end side, the challenges faced: to create a universal design that would reflect the need of the user on a global scale; to keep the features and the interface elements consistent throughout; to not compromise on the quality of the designs when the user zooms in on a detailed view of the map.

How will you use the time remaining to achieve a successful outcome?

For the time we have left, the team aims to focus on continuing to analyze user journeys, time-boxing tasks, conducting daily standups and holding retrospectives to plan, collaborate and deliver results and constantly refine features that will enable users to have an intuitive experience while also being able to successfully complete their task.
